    "full_text": "This is Joshua Tree National Park and it is a true desert climate. What does that mean? Well, for one, it means it gets very little rain over here, only about four to five inches in an entire year. And the air is extremely dry, which causes the land to heat up very quickly during the day and cool down very quickly at night. So, the daily temperatures can sometimes differ by about 50° Fahrenheit or even more. And yet some organisms live here just fine. For example, Joshua trees grow tall in the desert. We have kangaroo rats that survive without ever drinking liquid waters. And Chakala lizards can rest just fine on sunwarmmed rocks. But many organisms couldn't survive here at all. So that begs the question, why can some organisms live in a particular place while others can't? The answer has to do with the conditions and resources available in the environment. Okay, what do I mean by that? Every living thing from the largest plants and animals to the smallest microorganisms need certain things, certain resources to survive. Right now those resources can come from the living parts of the environment which we call the biotic factors and the non-living parts of the environment which we call the abiotic factors. It's the combination of these biotic and abiotic factors that decide which organisms can live in a particular environment and which can't. So let's talk about this in more detail. What are biotic factors? The biotic factors represent the living components of an environment necessary for survival of an organism. Which means this includes all the living beings. I'm talking about plants, animals, fungi, and even microorganisms like bacteria. And what are abiotic factors? They represent the non-living components of an environment necessary for an organism's survival. So think about air, sunlight, water, temperature and so much more. Let's take a couple of examples. Plants for example need sunlight and water in order to grow, right? These are abiotic factors. But many plants also depend on living organisms such as insects to pollinate them. So these are biotic factors. Another example, deer depends on grass for food, biotic factors. But it also depends on safe temperature ranges and access to water, for example. Abiotic factors. So together, the biotic and the abiotic factors explain why organisms live where they do and why they don't live elsewhere. So coming back to Joshua Tree National Park, what are some biotic factors over here? Well, think about this. Grasshoppers and chaka lizards, for example, depend on the bushes and the desert flowers that are available. So, that's a biotic factor. Kangaroo rats eat the seeds that are available over here. That's another biotic factor. Tarantulas feed on the grasshopper. So, they are also the biotic factors. So, like I said, all the living things that you can think of are the biotic factors. They're necessary for the survival of other living things that live over here. Okay, what are some abiotic factors over here? Well, they represent very limited rainfall, the extreme temperatures, the rocky and sandy soil that you find over here, and very intense sunlight. So, the very specific combination of biotic and abiotic factors that you find over here decides which organisms survive over here and which don't. If either type of factor is missing or changes too much, survival becomes difficult or even impossible. And what's also important is that these biotic and abiotic factors are limited. So organisms can often compete for them. For example, in dry environments, plants may compete for water in the soil and animals may compete for shade or for burrows that protect them from extreme heat during the day. So to summarize, organisms require a combination of the biotic and the abiotic factors to survive in an environment. The biotic factors include all the living components, plants, animals, fungi, and microorganisms. And the abiotic factors will include all the non-living components. And there are plenty of non-living components that are available over here. Here are some of these examples. Survival always depends on a combination of both."
